Hi,

I'm playing around with the smartTableCtrl  in order to set a sort function.

The table has by default a sort function in one of the columns as the values are to be sorted by date.
That all works perfectly. Clicking the column, changes the mode to asc or desc or disable the sorting. All fine.

The thing that is partially working is when I what to change the sort programmatically.

NOT WORKING
smartTableCtrl.sortBy(function sorter(row) {...}, reverse=true)

basically, it sorts the rows, but the icon is not updated with respect to asc or des.

Seems something happening in the stSort.js file.
```
//table state --> view
        scope.$watch(function () {
          return ctrl.tableState().sort;
        }, function (newValue) {
          if (newValue.predicate !== predicate) {
            index = 0;
            element
              .removeClass(classAscent)
              .removeClass(classDescent);
          } else {
            index = newValue.reverse === true ? 2 : 1;
            element
              .removeClass(stateClasses[index % 2])
              .addClass(stateClasses[index - 1]);
          }
        }, true);
```

Doing some breakpoint, shows that the reverse is not 'true'  (although it was true in the sortBy parameter)
and also, in the column that is to be evaluated.

the classes update wrong because:

index = 0
newValue.precate === predicate

therefore,

stateClasses[index - 1] = stateClasses[0 - 1] = stateClasses[-1]  = undefined

so addClass(undefined) of course does not give anything.



WORKING
For calling programmatically  the sortBy without functions, only string will work/sort fine.  i.e.    smartTableCtrl.sortBy('DueDate', true)

I've made ReplyKeyboardHide class, but it requires some changes in `convert_markup()` function, so, I'm leaving it to you:  
Here's the necessary class:  
```python
class ReplyKeyboardHide:
    def __init__(self, hide_keyboard=None, selective=None):
        self.hide_keyboard = hide_keyboard
        self.selective = selective

    def to_json(self):
        json_dict = {}
        if self.hide_keyboard:
            json_dict['hide_keyboard'] = True
        if self.selective:
            json_dict['selective'] = True
        return json.dumps(json_dict)
```

