A quick look gives:
```
$ git grep calloc
c_speech_features/c_speech_features.c:    energy = (csf_float*)calloc(sizeof(csf_float), n_frames);
c_speech_features/c_speech_features.c:  feat = (csf_float*)calloc(sizeof(csf_float), n_frames * aNFilters);
c_speech_features/c_speech_features.c:  feat = (csf_float*)calloc(sizeof(csf_float), n_frames * aNFilters);
c_speech_features/c_speech_features.c:  ssc = (csf_float*)calloc(sizeof(csf_float*), n_frames * aNFilters);
c_speech_features/c_speech_features.c:  delta = (csf_float*)calloc(sizeof(csf_float), aNFrames * aNFrameLen);
c_speech_features/c_speech_features.c:    (csf_float*)calloc(sizeof(csf_float), aNFilters * feat_width);
c_speech_features/c_speech_features.c:  win_correct = (csf_float*)calloc(sizeof(csf_float), aSigLen);
c_speech_features/c_speech_features.c:  signal = (csf_float*)calloc(sizeof(csf_float), aSigLen);
```

While manpage states:
```
       void *calloc(size_t nmemb, size_t size);
[...]
       The calloc() function allocates memory for an array of nmemb elements of size bytes each and returns a pointer to the allocated memory.  The memory is set to zero.  If nmemb or size is 0, then calloc() returns either NULL, or a unique pointer
       value that can later be successfully passed to free().
```

So the first argument is the number of elements, and the second argument is the size of each one of them. Our calls are inverting both.

Hello,

I'm trying to load an FBX and Converter::ConvertMeshMultiMaterial does not behave as expected:

https://github.com/assimp/assimp/blob/master/code/FBXConverter.cpp#L1031

The problem is the loop in this method clearly expect `mindices` and `faces` to have the same size. In my case they do not (I can't share the FBX file, it's under NDA). What might cause this?

As workaround, I've modified the calling function to avoid going any further if the sizes don't match:

https://github.com/assimp/assimp/blob/master/code/FBXConverter.cpp#L1031

becomes

```
std::vector<unsigned int> ConvertMeshMultiMaterial(const MeshGeometry& mesh, const Model& model, 
        const aiMatrix4x4& node_global_transform)    
    {
        const MatIndexArray& mindices = mesh.GetMaterialIndices();
        ai_assert(mindices.size());
    
        std::set<MatIndexArray::value_type> had;
        std::vector<unsigned int> indices;

        BOOST_FOREACH(MatIndexArray::value_type index, mindices) {
            if (had.find(index) == had.end() && mesh.GetFaceIndexCounts().size() == mindices.size()) {

                indices.push_back(ConvertMeshMultiMaterial(mesh, model, index, node_global_transform));
                had.insert(index);
            }
        }

        return indices;
    }
```

The only change is the second check in the if to make sure sizes match.

What do you think?

Regards,

Description: Unable to [create a Glue Crawler](https://boto3.readthedocs.io/en/latest/reference/services/glue.html#Glue.Client.create_crawler) using the glue_client.create_crawler() using DynamoDBTargets as a Target. Receive:
```
botocore.exceptions.ParamValidationError: Parameter validation failed:
Unknown parameter in Targets: "DynamoDBTargets", must be one of: S3Targets, JdbcTargets"
```

Recreate: Install boto3-1.7.58 and attempt to create a Glue Crawler with DynamoDB as the target.

Versions:
        Python interpreter: Python 2.7.12
        Boto 3:
        Package         Version
        --------------- -------
        boto3           1.7.58 
        botocore        1.10.58

```
import boto3

glue_client = boto3.client('glue')

response = glue_client.create_crawler(
    Name='crawlMeDynamoDB',
    Role='arn:aws:iam::123456789012:role/service-role/AWSGlueServiceRole-DynamoDB',
    DatabaseName='dynamoDB',
    Targets={
        'DynamoDBTargets': [
            {
                'Path': 'ProductCatalog'
            },
            {
                'Path': 'Forum'
            },
            {
                'Path': 'Reply'
            },
            {
                'Path': 'Thread'
            },
        ]
    }
)

print response
```

