It would be nice to be able to pass structured NumPy scalars back to C++, e.g.:

```c++
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/numpy.h>
#include <vector>

struct A { int a; float b; A() = default; A(int a) : a(a), b(a + 1) {} };

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(test_scalars) {
    PYBIND11_NUMPY_DTYPE(A, a, b);
    return pybind11::module("test_scalars")
        .def("f_struct", [](A a) { return (float) a.a + a.b; })
        .def("mk_structs", []() {
                std::vector<A> x {A(1), A(2), A(3)};
                return pybind11::array_t<A>(3, x.data());
            })
        .ptr();
}
```

It would be great to have this work:

```python
>>> from test_scalars import *
>>> f_struct(mk_structs()[1])
```

(it already works with arithmetic NumPy types, but mostly because they inherit from the builtins)

Because structured types are always POD, they're default constructible and don't have a user destructor; so basically all we need to do is a reinterpret cast. Each element  of the structured array is of type `np.void`:

```python
>>>  mk_structs()
array([(1, 2.0), (2, 3.0), (3, 4.0)], dtype=[('a', '<i4'), ('b', '<f4')])
>>> row = mk_structs()[1]; row
(2, 3.0)
>>> type(row).mro()
[numpy.void, numpy.flexible, numpy.generic, object]
>>> row.dtype
dtype([('a', '<i4'), ('b', '<f4')])
>>> row.data.tolist()
[2, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 64, 64]
```

